=========================================================
DOUBT : WHY DO EXTRA NODES APPEAR IN ros2 node list?
=========================================================

DOUBT
-----

The tutorial shows only a few nodes:

    /robot_state_publisher
    /teleop_keyboard

But when I run:

    ros2 node list

I see:

    /gazebo
    /robot_state_publisher
    /teleop_keyboard
    /turtlebot3_diff_drive
    /turtlebot3_imu
    /turtlebot3_joint_state
    /turtlebot3_laserscan

Why are these extra nodes appearing?
Is something wrong with my setup?


EXPLANATION
-----------

Nothing is wrong.

The TurtleBot3 simulation loads additional plugins and sensors
that automatically create extra ROS2 nodes.

The tutorial only showed the most important nodes and did not
show every node running in the system.

The additional nodes are:

1. /turtlebot3_diff_drive

   Purpose:
   - Controls the robot wheels.
   - Receives velocity commands from the topic:

         /cmd_vel

   - Converts those commands into wheel movement.

---------------------------------------------------------

2. /turtlebot3_imu

   Purpose:
   - Simulates the IMU (Inertial Measurement Unit).
   - Publishes orientation and acceleration data.

---------------------------------------------------------

3. /turtlebot3_joint_state

   Purpose:
   - Publishes the state of the wheel joints.
   - Tells ROS how the wheels are rotating.

---------------------------------------------------------

4. /turtlebot3_laserscan

   Purpose:
   - Simulates the LiDAR sensor.
   - Publishes distance measurements of the surroundings.

---------------------------------------------------------

5. /gazebo

   Purpose:
   - The Gazebo simulation server itself.
   - Responsible for running the physics simulation.

---------------------------------------------------------

HOW THESE NODES ARE CREATED
---------------------------

The launch file:

    empty_world.launch.py

does NOT directly contain the code for these nodes.

Instead:

    empty_world.launch.py
            ↓
    spawn_turtlebot3.launch.py
            ↓
    TurtleBot3 Burger Model (SDF)
            ↓
    Gazebo Plugins
            ↓
    ROS2 Nodes

Inside the Burger model file there are plugin definitions such as:

    <plugin name="turtlebot3_diff_drive" ...>
    <plugin name="turtlebot3_imu" ...>
    <plugin name="turtlebot3_laserscan" ...>
    <plugin name="turtlebot3_joint_state" ...>

When Gazebo loads the robot model, these plugins are loaded
automatically and create the corresponding ROS2 nodes because these nodes are coded in turtlebot3_simulations in model/burger; that means these nodes will load whenever we spawn robot. 

---------------------------------------------------------

IMPORTANT CONCLUSION
--------------------

More nodes than the tutorial shows does NOT mean there is an error.

It simply means the TurtleBot3 simulation is loading additional
controllers and sensors.

As long as:

    /robot_state_publisher
    /teleop_keyboard

are present and the robot can move correctly, your setup is working
as expected.

=========================================================
CHILD-LIKE EXPLANATION
=========================================================

Think of the launch file as a command:

    "Bring the robot into the room."

When the robot enters the room, it brings:

    - Wheels
    - LiDAR
    - IMU
    - Joint sensors

Each of these creates its own helper node.

So instead of seeing only two people in the room,
you see the robot's whole team working together.

That is why extra nodes appear in:

    ros2 node list

# ROS 2, Gazebo, Plugins, Topics, Publishers, Subscribers, and Bridges

## Why I Wrote These Notes

While following Tom Howard's ROS 2 course, I noticed that my RQT graph looked different from the tutorial.

The tutorial showed:

```text
/teleop_keyboard
      |
      v
   /cmd_vel
      |
      v
 /ros_gz_bridge
      |
      +--> /scan
      +--> /imu
      +--> /joint_states
      +--> /odom
```

My setup showed:

```text
/teleop_keyboard --> /cmd_vel --> /turtlebot3_diff_drive
/turtlebot3_laserscan --> /scan
/turtlebot3_imu --> /imu
/turtlebot3_joint_state --> /joint_states
```

This led to an important question:

> Why is my setup different even though I followed the tutorial?

To answer that, we first need to understand some ROS fundamentals.

---

# 1. What is a Node?

A node is a running ROS program.

Examples:

```text
/teleop_keyboard
/robot_state_publisher
/turtlebot3_laserscan
```

Each node performs one specific task.

Examples:

| Node                  | Responsibility           |
| --------------------- | ------------------------ |
| teleop_keyboard       | Read keyboard input      |
| robot_state_publisher | Publish robot transforms |
| turtlebot3_laserscan  | Publish LiDAR data       |
| turtlebot3_imu        | Publish IMU data         |

Think of a node as a worker in a company.

Each worker has one job.

---

# 2. What is a Topic?

Nodes need a way to communicate.

ROS uses Topics.

A topic is like a radio channel.

Example:

```text
/cmd_vel
```

means:

"Velocity Command"

A node can broadcast messages on this channel and other nodes can listen.

Example:

```text
teleop_keyboard
      |
      v
   /cmd_vel
      |
      v
turtlebot3_diff_drive
```

The keyboard node sends movement commands.

The drive controller receives them.

---

# 3. What is Publishing?

Publishing means:

> Sending data onto a topic.

Example:

```text
teleop_keyboard
```

publishes:

```text
/cmd_vel
```

When you press:

```text
W
```

it publishes:

```text
Move forward
```

When you press:

```text
A
```

it publishes:

```text
Turn left
```

---

# 4. What is Subscribing?

Subscribing means:

> Listening to data from a topic.

Example:

```text
turtlebot3_diff_drive
```

subscribes to:

```text
/cmd_vel
```

It listens for movement commands.

Whenever a message arrives, it moves the wheels.

---

# 5. Publisher-Subscriber Relationship

Example:

```text
Publisher
    |
    v
/cmd_vel
    |
    v
Subscriber
```

More specifically:

```text
teleop_keyboard
       |
       v
    /cmd_vel
       |
       v
turtlebot3_diff_drive
```

Publisher:

```text
teleop_keyboard
```

Topic:

```text
/cmd_vel
```

Subscriber:

```text
turtlebot3_diff_drive
```

---

# 6. What is a Plugin?

A plugin is an add-on module that gives extra functionality.
Gazebo-ros plugin means communication between gazebo simulation and ros ;just like what bridge does 

Think of a robot model.

Without plugins:

```text
Robot exists
```

With plugins:

```text
Robot can move
Robot can publish IMU data
Robot can publish LiDAR data
Robot can publish wheel states
```

In Gazebo, plugins are usually compiled C++ libraries.

Example:

```xml
<plugin
    name="turtlebot3_diff_drive"
    filename="libgazebo_ros_diff_drive.so">
```

This plugin:

```text
Reads wheel commands
Moves wheels
Publishes odometry
Creates ROS interfaces
```

---

# 7. What Happens When Gazebo Loads a Plugin?

When Gazebo sees:

```xml
<plugin name="turtlebot3_laserscan" ...>
```

it loads:

```text
libgazebo_ros_ray_sensor.so
```

That plugin starts working and creates:

```text
/turtlebot3_laserscan
```

which publishes:

```text
/scan
```

The same happens for:

```text
/turtlebot3_imu
/turtlebot3_joint_state
/turtlebot3_diff_drive
```

---

# 8. Plugin-Based Architecture

My TurtleBot3 setup uses plugins.

Architecture:

```text
Gazebo
   |
   v
Gazebo ROS Plugin
   |
   v
ROS Topic
```

Example:

```text
Gazebo
   |
   v
libgazebo_ros_ray_sensor.so
   |
   v
/scan
```

No bridge is required.

Advantages:

* Simpler
* Faster
* Fewer processes
* Common in Gazebo Classic

---

# 9. What is a Bridge?

A bridge is a translator.

Imagine:

```text
ROS 2 speaks English
Gazebo speaks Japanese
```

The bridge translates.

Architecture:

```text
Gazebo
   |
   v
Bridge
   |
   v
ROS
```

Example:

```text
Gazebo Laser
      |
      v
ros_gz_bridge
      |
      v
ROS LaserScan
```

---

# 10. Bridge-Based Architecture

Architecture:

```text
Gazebo Topic
      |
      v
ros_gz_bridge
      |
      v
ROS Topic
```

Example:

```text
Gazebo
      |
      v
Laser Topic
      |
      v
ros_gz_bridge
      |
      v
/scan
```

Advantages:

* Cleaner separation
* Modern Gazebo architecture
* Works with Gazebo Sim (Ignition)

---

# 11. Why Does the Tutorial Show ros_gz_bridge?

The tutorial likely uses:

```text
Gazebo Sim (Ignition)
```

which communicates through Gazebo Transport messages.

ROS 2 cannot directly understand those messages.

Therefore:

```text
ros_gz_bridge
```

is required.

The bridge translates:

```text
Gazebo Message
      ↔
ROS Message
```

---

# 12. Why Is My Setup Different?

Even though I followed the tutorial, I installed and ran TurtleBot3 using:

```text
turtlebot3_gazebo
```

which uses Gazebo ROS plugins.

The TurtleBot3 Burger model contains:

```xml
libgazebo_ros_diff_drive.so
libgazebo_ros_imu_sensor.so
libgazebo_ros_ray_sensor.so
libgazebo_ros_joint_state_publisher.so
```

These plugins already connect Gazebo directly to ROS.

Therefore:

```text
No ros_gz_bridge is needed
```

My setup is:

```text
Plugin-Based
```

The tutorial example is:

```text
Bridge-Based
```

Both are valid.

---

# 13. How Can I Tell Which Architecture I Am Using?

If RQT shows:

```text
/ros_gz_bridge
```

you are using:

```text
Bridge Architecture
```

If RQT shows:

```text
/turtlebot3_laserscan
/turtlebot3_imu
/turtlebot3_diff_drive
```

you are using:

```text
Plugin Architecture
```

---

# 14. How Can I Switch To Bridge Architecture?

Current:

```text
Gazebo Classic
+
Gazebo ROS Plugins
```

To use bridge architecture, I would need:

1. Gazebo Sim (Ignition)
2. ros_gz packages
3. ros_gz_bridge
4. Launch files configured for Gazebo Sim

Typical bridge command:

```bash
ros2 run ros_gz_bridge parameter_bridge
```

with specific topics configured.

This is not usually done by editing TurtleBot3 plugin files.

Instead, it involves changing the entire simulation stack.

---

# Final Summary

Plugin Architecture:

```text
Gazebo
   |
Plugin
   |
ROS Topic
```

Bridge Architecture:

```text
Gazebo
   |
Bridge
   |
ROS Topic
```

My TurtleBot3 setup uses plugins because the TurtleBot3 Burger model contains Gazebo ROS plugins.

The tutorial screenshot uses a bridge-based setup, likely based on Gazebo Sim.

Both approaches achieve the same goal:

Getting data between Gazebo and ROS.
